# **EXERCISE 1: SINGLE-TASK SPRINTS**

The foundational lift. The bench press for your brain. This is where you translate that raw, pissed-off awareness into measurable output. Forget multitasking; here, we worship at the altar of the one thing. The goal is not duration, but purity of attention.

**The Setup:** You will need a task (report, spreadsheet, email draft), a timer, and a physical token. Acoaster, a pen, a weird little figurine from your desk. This is your “Focus Token.”

**The Execution:** Place the token in front of you. Set your timer for **12 minutes**. Not 10, not 15. Twelve. It’s just long enough to be challenging, just short enough to not trigger panic. Your rule is monastic: one task, full screen, zero deviation. If you need to research, you make a note [LOOK THIS UP] and keep going. If you think of something else, you jot it on a notepad and return to the sprint.

The token is crucial. It’s a sensory anchor. Your fingers might itch. Pick up the token. Feel its weight, its texture. It is the physical manifestation of your commitment for these twelve minutes. It is your job.

I tried this with Leo, a graphic designer who could start a logo but would inevitably drift into scrolling design blogs, “for inspiration.” His token was a smooth, cold river stone.

“First sprint,” he told me later, voice tense. “I got about four minutes in. My brain was screaming. It was like it was throwing a tantrum, throwing images of fonts and color palettes at me. I actually picked up the stone and held it so tight my knuckles went white. I just kept whispering, ‘The logo. Just the logo.’ It was… embarrassingly hard.”

But he finished the twelve. The logo wasn’t perfect, but it had a shape it didn’t have before.

**The Science:** This is **interval training**, borrowed from elite athletics. Short, maximal-effort bursts followed by rest. You’re teaching your prefrontal cortex—the CEO of your brain—to maintain executive control under fatigue. You’re also starving the dopamine-seeking part of your brain that thrives on task-switching. Every time you resist the switch, you weaken that neural craving.

**The Cooldown:** When the timer rings, you *must* stop. Put the token down. Stand up. Walk for five minutes. Look out a window. Do not, under any circumstances, check social media or news. This is active recovery. You’re letting the mental metabolites clear.

**Progression:** Your “Focus PR” (Personal Record) is your baseline number of quality sprints in a session. Start with two. Next session, aim for two sprints that feel 10% more solid. That’s the goal: not necessarily longer time, but denseHe’d forgotten it. The muscle memory was taking over. The stone, once a central character in his struggle, had become a mere piece of the scenery, its weight irrelevant against the rhythm of his breath and the burn in his legs. For now, the battle was won not through confrontation, but through a kind of focused oblivion.

