This is where we get sneaky. If Single-Task Sprints are about building pure strength, the Drop-Set is about building resilience and control. It’s boxing wit. The principle is simple: just as you’ve locked into your rhythm, we introduce a calculated variable. Not to break your focus, but to teach it how to bend. Leo would learn this the hard way the following Monday, when Coach Vance placed a second, smaller stone beside the first with a grim smile. “You’ve learned to ignore one,” he said. “Now let’s see you ignore two.”h your distractions.

**The Setup:** For your next sprint, you will intentionally introduce a distraction. Place your phone, face-up, next to your Focus Token. Open a tab with a mildly interesting website—a news site, a blog you like. Have it visible, but muted.

**The Execution:** Start your sprint. Work. The distraction is right there, pulsing with potential. Your peripheral vision will catch the screen. Your mind will tug you toward it. Your job is to acknowledge its presence, and then, with deliberate force, dismiss it. Look at the phone, and then physically turn your head back to your work. See the open tab, and with your mouse, *click it closed*. Don’t just minimize it. Kill it.

This is a drop-set: you’re adding weight (the distraction) and then forcing the muscle (focus) to work even as it begs you to stop.

Maya, a writer battling a constant urge to “just quickly check” her group chats, used this. She opened a particularly active chat window beside her document.

“It felt like torture,” she admitted, a laugh in her voice. “Seeing the little notification bubble pop up with a ‘(3)’. My whole body tensed. The first time, I caved after six minutes. I felt so defeated. But the next time, I saw the (3), and instead of clicking, I highlighted a whole paragraph in my doc and deleted it. A brutal, physical act of choosing my work. Closing that chat window after felt better than reading the messages ever could.”

**The Science:** You are practicing **inhibitory control**. You are strengthening the neural “brake pedal.” By making the distraction overt and then choosing to resist it, you’re not just avoiding temptation; you’re actively rehearsing the act of suppression. Each time you close that tab, you’re carving the path deeper: “See distraction. Apply brake. Return to task.”

**The Cooldown:** After this sprint, your rest must be completely analog. No screens. Stretch. Make tea. The contrast is part of the training.

