# **EXERCISE 3: THE PERIPHERAL VISION CLEANSE**

Our focus isn’t just internal; it’s besieged by the external. This drill is a sensory reset, a tactical strike against environmental chaos.

**The Setup:** Sit at your workspace. Don’t start working.

**The Execution:** For one minute, you will do nothing but consciously note everything in your peripheral vision. The stack of papers tilting left. The dust on the monitor rim. the way the light from the window hits the floor. The flicker of the router LED. Don’t judge it, don’t plan to clean it. Just see it. Acknowledge its existence.

Then, for the next minute, you will eliminate or minimize three things you noted. Straighten the stack. Wipe the dust. Turn the router around. You are not “cleaning.” You are **de-cluttering your sensory field**. You are removing the tiny, unconscious drains on your attentional resources.

Sam, a programmer working from a cluttered dining table, was skeptical. “It’s just stuff,” he said. But he did it. He noted the cereal bowl from breakfast, his son’s drawing tucked under a laptop stand, a jacket slung over a chair.

“After I moved them,” he said, his tone surprised, “it was like a low-grade hum I didn’t know was there just… stopped. The space felt quieter, even though no actual noise changed. The next sprint I did felt cleaner. Like there were fewer hooks in the air trying to catch my thoughts.”

**The Science:** This tackles **attentional capture**. Our brains are hardwired to monitor our environment for change. Every irregular object, every bit of visual noise, is a potential “alert” waiting to be processed, if only subconsciously. By consciously surveying and curating your periphery, you’re switching your brain from a passive, alert state to an active, controlled one. You’re telling your thalamus (the brain’s sensory gatekeeper), “I’ve seen it. I’ve handled it. Stand down.”

